In-Class Exercise 1: ArtyBot Foward Kinematics

Your task is to validate our model of Forward Kinematics (FK). You can use the "easy" solution that only involves trig, or (and much more importantly) you can use the general approach that leverages homogeneous transformations.

  • GOAL: Write a function that produces and estimate of $^A\vec{P}$ based on $\theta_2,\theta_3$**

In-Class Exercise 2: ArtyBot Inverse Kinematics

In the ArtyBot webots world, implement the inverse kinematic equations we derived in class.

  1. Draw a box using ArtyBot
  2. Build a FSM and program to draw any arbitrary shape separated by lists of points in the XY (allocentric) plane using Arty. Program should read a text file that describes what it needs to draw. File should have 3 columns: Drawing (boolean), X (m) Y (m) FSM should lift pen if "Drawing" column contains a 0, and should place pen on paper when "Drawing" column contains a 1.

HINTS for exercise 2.1

  • Above the loop:
    • define a box by xy points (an array)
      • points = np.array([[.08, 0],[.08,.02],[.1,0.02],[.1,0.0]])
      • Define a "box point index" variable starting at 0 that you will increment to draw the "next" point in your array.
    • Define a FSM timer that represents how long to "dwell" on any one commanded point. Don't need a whole FSM for exercise 1, but you will for exercise 2.
  • In the loop:
    • Update timer so that it's enabled if its status bit isn't true. This will create an "auto-firing" timer that continuously resets itself at a known interval
    • When the timer status bit goes true, increment the "box point index" variable by 1
    • If you've gone through all the points, reset this index to 0.
    • Now use your IK formula to find theta1, theta2
    • Now convert theta1,theta2 to servo angles
    • Then send servo angles to robot.
    • Plot GPS pen position and "box points" together
